alternatives.transcript: mister palmer today so mister palmer presented with complaint of shortness of breath and fatigue that had been ongoing for the past six months he said that this was kind of just mild for six months and then over the last three days it started progressively worsening so he went to his primary care physician who ordered a few tests which he was not sure of the name of however when his symptoms significantly worsened today he called his pcp again who referred him to the emergency department patient stated that his shortness of breath is worse with lying flat and with any type of exertion at all such as just walking around and he feels a little bit better when he lays back on an incline when i walked in the room his vitals showed a blood pressure of eighty over fifty with an spo two of eighty six and a heart rate of ninety beats per minute his past medical history was significant for hyperlipidemia hypertension diabetes atrial fibrillation and coronary artery disease with a coronary bar coronary artery bypass graft times three twelve years ago with an additional stent placed more recently he remembers having an echo done that showed an ef of about forty percent a few years ago he's currently smoking one pack per day and was at home with his wife on exam he had positive jugular venous distension he was tachycardic with a split s two and had no murmurs rubs or gallops his pmi was displaced laterally and he had one plus lower extremity edema with no associated calf tenderness after reviewing his results we discussed that his chest x-ray showed pulmonary edema with cardiomegaly his ekg showed a normal sinus rhythm with a left axis deviation and a left bundle branch block and his lab showed elevated troponin and a bnp significantly elevated at four thousand his most recent echo that he had done with us showed an injection fraction of thirty percent and a dilated left ventricle given this i diagnosed mister palmer with ischemic dilated cardiomyopathy with plan to admit him to the icu reorder his ptinr and serial troponins and i kept him on clopidogrel warfarin lisinopril and started him on dobutamine as a positive ionotropic agent i also told him that the interventional cardiologist would be coming by to consult and discuss aicd crt placement to also assist with increasing the heart's pumping power and to consider that as a potential medical device to conclude patient had no questions for me and was agreeable with the plan thank you
